<h2 id="types">Types of Coverage Available in {{ state.name }}</h2>

<p>Beyond the state minimum, {{ state.name }} drivers should consider the following coverage types for comprehensive protection:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Collision coverage:</strong> Pays for damage to your vehicle after an accident, regardless of fault. Required if your vehicle is financed or leased.</li>
  <li><strong>Comprehensive coverage:</strong> Covers theft, vandalism, weather damage, animal strikes, and other non-collision events. Also typically required for financed vehicles.</li>
  <li><strong>Uninsured/underinsured motorist coverage:</strong> Protects you if you are hit by a driver with no insurance or insufficient coverage. Highly recommended in every state.</li>
  <li><strong>Medical payments / PIP:</strong> Covers medical expenses for you and your passengers regardless of fault. PIP (Personal Injury Protection) may be required in {{ state.name }}.</li>
  <li><strong>Roadside assistance:</strong> Covers towing, battery jumps, flat tire changes, and lockout services. Usually affordable at $2-5 per month.</li>
  <li><strong>Gap coverage:</strong> Pays the difference between your vehicle's actual cash value and what you owe on your loan if the car is totaled. Essential for new cars with loans.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="filing-claim">Filing an Insurance Claim in {{ state.name }}</h2>

<p>If you are involved in an accident in {{ state.name }}, follow these steps to protect your insurance claim:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Ensure everyone is safe and call 911 if there are injuries.</li>
  <li>Exchange information with the other driver(s): name, phone, insurance company, policy number, and license plate.</li>
  <li>Document the scene with photos and video from multiple angles.</li>
  <li>File a police report, even for minor accidents. This creates an official record that supports your claim.</li>
  <li>Contact your insurance company as soon as possible. Most insurers have 24/7 claims lines.</li>
  <li>Keep records of all expenses related to the accident, including medical bills, rental car costs, and lost wages.</li>
</ol>

<p>If your claim is denied or you believe you are not receiving fair compensation, consider consulting with an auto accident attorney who is licensed in {{ state.name }}.</p>

